ng" in understanding shifts in American religion. It reveals how the Christian world hosts a culture of celebrity very similar to the secular realm, particularly in terms of marketing, branding, and publicity. Holy Mavericks reaffirms that religion is always in conversation with the larger society in which it is embedded, and that it is imperative to understand how those religious suppliers who are able to change with the times will outlast those who are not.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChurch marketingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPopular culturexReligious aspectsxProtestant churchesxHistory. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aProtestant churcheszUnited StatesxClergyxHistory. 4adecline. 4aevangelical. 4ainsights. 4ainto. 4aleadership. 4amovements. 4aothers. 4aperspectives. 4areligious. 4asome. 4athrive. 4awhile. 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Evangelism.2bisacsh1 aLee, Shayne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814753453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814753453.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK